WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.516
How does a strand of DNA become the sticky glue

2
00:00:02.616 --> 00:00:05.411
that holds sand together? It happens in three steps.

3
00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:10.516
First, the gene is copied into a short-lived message called messenger R-N-A.

4
00:00:10.616 --> 00:00:14.119
This copy does not last — it is made and destroyed constantly.

5
00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:16.261
That message is then read to build the enzyme

6
00:00:16.361 --> 00:00:18.566
— the molecular machine that does the real work.

7
00:00:19.966 --> 00:00:23.286
The enzyme grabs glutamate units, one after another, and

8
00:00:23.386 --> 00:00:26.401
stitches them into a long chain — gamma-P-G-A. This

9
00:00:26.501 --> 00:00:28.722
is the polymer that becomes our crust.

10
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.816
But the cell also carries genes whose enzymes chew that

11
00:00:32.916 --> 00:00:35.255
chain back up. So we knock those scissors out.

12
00:00:36.133 --> 00:00:39.643
With no scissors, the gamma-P-G-A no longer gets cut back —

13
00:00:39.743 --> 00:00:42.642
so it piles up, and the crust gets what it needs.

14
00:00:44.533 --> 00:00:49.163
Gene, message, enzyme, polymer — four steps, tracked in time. That is how

15
00:00:49.263 --> 00:00:52.661
a line of code in the DNA turns into glue in the sand.

